---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import AdUnit from '../../components/AdUnit.astro';
import { getWorksheetBySlug } from '../../data/worksheets';
import '../../styles/worksheet.css';

const ws = getWorksheetBySlug('one-step-equations-worksheets')!;

const structuredData = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "BreadcrumbList",
  "itemListElement": [
    {
      "@type": "ListItem",
      "position": 1,
      "name": "Home",
      "item": "https://toolcalcs.com/"
    },
    {
      "@type": "ListItem",
      "position": 2,
      "name": "Worksheets",
      "item": "https://toolcalcs.com/worksheets/"
    },
    {
      "@type": "ListItem",
      "position": 3,
      "name": "One-Step Equations"
    }
  ]
};
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Free One-Step Equations Worksheets - Printable Math Practice | ToolCalcs"
  description={ws.description}
  type="article"
  structuredData={structuredData}
>
  <nav class="breadcrumb">
    <a href="/">Home</a> &rsaquo;
    <a href="/worksheets/">Worksheets</a> &rsaquo;
    <span>One-Step Equations</span>
  </nav>

  <h1>{ws.title}</h1>
  <p class="page-desc">{ws.description}</p>

  <div class="worksheet-box">
    <div class="config-panel">
      <h3>Settings</h3>
      <div class="config-inputs">
        <div class="config-group">
          <label for="cfgProblems">Number of Problems</label>
          <input type="number" id="cfgProblems" value="15" min="5" max="30" />
        </div>
        <div class="config-group">
          <label for="cfgOperation">Operation</label>
          <select id="cfgOperation">
            <option value="add">Addition</option>
            <option value="subtract">Subtraction</option>
            <option value="multiply">Multiplication</option>
            <option value="divide">Division</option>
            <option value="mixed" selected>Mixed</option>
          </select>
        </div>
        <div class="config-group">
          <label for="cfgRange">Number Range</label>
          <select id="cfgRange">
            <option value="20" selected>Up to 20</option>
            <option value="50">Up to 50</option>
            <option value="100">Up to 100</option>
          </select>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="worksheet-actions">
      <button class="ws-btn primary" id="btnGenerate">Generate New</button>
      <button class="ws-btn print" id="btnPrint">Print</button>
      <label class="toggle-label">
        <input type="checkbox" id="toggleAnswers" />
        Show Answers
      </label>
    </div>

    <div class="worksheet-content" id="worksheetContent">
      <div class="worksheet-header-print">
        <h2>One-Step Equations Practice</h2>
        <div class="name-date">
          <span>Name: ___________________</span>
          <span>Date: ___________________</span>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-grid" id="problemGrid"></div>
      <div class="answer-key hidden" id="answerKey">
        <h3>Answer Key</h3>
        <div class="answer-grid" id="answerGrid"></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <AdUnit slot="ws-mid" format="rectangle" />

  <article class="content-section">
    <h2>What Are One-Step Equations?</h2>
    <p>A one-step equation is an algebraic equation that can be solved in a single operation. These equations take forms like x + 5 = 12, x - 3 = 7, 4x = 20, or x/6 = 3. The goal is to isolate the variable (usually x) on one side of the equation by performing the inverse operation. One-step equations are the first formal introduction to algebra for most students and serve as the foundation for solving more complex equations in later grades.</p>
    <p>These free printable one-step equations worksheets are designed for students in grades 6 and 7. They provide structured practice with all four operations, and the configurable settings let you focus on a single operation type or mix all four. The number range setting controls the size of the values used, allowing you to match the difficulty to your student's current skill level. Every click of "Generate New" produces a fresh set of problems with integer solutions.</p>

    <h2>How to Solve One-Step Equations</h2>
    <h3>Addition Equations (x + a = b)</h3>
    <p>To solve an addition equation, subtract the same number from both sides. For example, x + 7 = 15 becomes x = 15 - 7 = 8. The inverse of addition is subtraction, and performing the same operation on both sides keeps the equation balanced.</p>

    <h3>Subtraction Equations (x - a = b)</h3>
    <p>To solve a subtraction equation, add the same number to both sides. For example, x - 4 = 9 becomes x = 9 + 4 = 13. Adding undoes the subtraction and reveals the value of x.</p>

    <h3>Multiplication Equations (ax = b)</h3>
    <p>To solve a multiplication equation, divide both sides by the coefficient. For example, 6x = 42 becomes x = 42 / 6 = 7. Division is the inverse of multiplication.</p>

    <h3>Division Equations (x/a = b)</h3>
    <p>To solve a division equation, multiply both sides by the divisor. For example, x/5 = 8 becomes x = 8 times 5 = 40. Multiplication undoes the division.</p>

    <h2>The Balance Model</h2>
    <p>One of the most effective ways to teach equation solving is the balance model. Imagine a balance scale where the left side equals the right side. Whatever you do to one side, you must do to the other to keep it balanced. This physical metaphor helps students understand why we perform the same operation on both sides of an equation. Many teachers use actual balance scales with weights in class to demonstrate this concept before transitioning to symbolic manipulation.</p>

    <h2>Tips for Parents and Teachers</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Start with a single operation.</strong> Let students master addition equations before moving to subtraction, then multiplication, and finally division. Once each type is comfortable, switch to Mixed for comprehensive review.</li>
      <li><strong>Emphasize inverse operations.</strong> The key insight is that each operation has an inverse: addition undoes subtraction, multiplication undoes division, and vice versa. Students who internalize this pattern can solve any one-step equation.</li>
      <li><strong>Have students check their answers.</strong> After finding x, substitute it back into the original equation to verify. This habit catches errors and reinforces the meaning of a solution.</li>
      <li><strong>Use the number range to control difficulty.</strong> Start with Up to 20 for manageable arithmetic, then progress to Up to 50 and Up to 100 as confidence grows.</li>
      <li><strong>Write out each step.</strong> Encourage students to write the inverse operation on both sides rather than doing the work mentally. Showing work builds habits that are essential for multi-step equations later.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Related Worksheets</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><a href="/worksheets/two-step-equations-worksheets/">Two-Step Equations Worksheets</a> &ndash; The natural next step after mastering one-step equations.</li>
      <li><a href="/worksheets/algebra-worksheets/">Algebra Worksheets</a> &ndash; Broader algebra practice including expressions and simplification.</li>
      <li><a href="/worksheets/integers-worksheets/">Integers Worksheets</a> &ndash; Build integer operation skills needed for equations with negative numbers.</li>
    </ul>
  </article>

  <AdUnit slot="ws-bottom" format="horizontal" />
</BaseLayout>

<script is:inline>
  var problems = [];

  function randInt(min, max) {
    return Math.floor(Math.random() * (max - min + 1)) + min;
  }

  function generateProblems() {
    var count = parseInt(document.getElementById('cfgProblems').value, 10);
    var operation = document.getElementById('cfgOperation').value;
    var range = parseInt(document.getElementById('cfgRange').value, 10);

    if (isNaN(count) || count < 5) count = 5;
    if (count > 30) count = 30;

    problems = [];
    var ops = ['add', 'subtract', 'multiply', 'divide'];

    for (var i = 0; i < count; i++) {
      var op = operation === 'mixed' ? ops[randInt(0, 3)] : operation;
      var x, a, result, text, answer;

      if (op === 'add') {
        // x + a = result
        x = randInt(1, range);
        a = randInt(1, range);
        result = x + a;
        text = 'x + ' + a + ' = ' + result;
        answer = x;
      } else if (op === 'subtract') {
        // x - a = result
        x = randInt(1, range);
        a = randInt(1, x); // ensure positive result sometimes
        result = x - a;
        text = 'x &ndash; ' + a + ' = ' + result;
        answer = x;
      } else if (op === 'multiply') {
        // a * x = result
        a = randInt(2, Math.min(12, range));
        x = randInt(1, Math.floor(range / a));
        result = a * x;
        text = a + 'x = ' + result;
        answer = x;
      } else {
        // x / a = result
        a = randInt(2, Math.min(12, range));
        result = randInt(1, Math.floor(range / a));
        x = a * result;
        text = 'x / ' + a + ' = ' + result;
        answer = x;
      }

      problems.push({ text: text, answer: answer });
    }

    renderProblems();
    renderAnswerKey();
    updateAnswerVisibility();
  }

  function renderProblems() {
    var grid = document.getElementById('problemGrid');
    var showAnswers = document.getElementById('toggleAnswers').checked;
    var html = '';

    for (var i = 0; i < problems.length; i++) {
      var p = problems[i];
      html += '<div class="problem">';
      html += '<div class="problem-number">' + (i + 1) + ')</div>';
      html += '<div class="problem-text">' + p.text + '</div>';
      html += '<div class="problem-answer' + (showAnswers ? ' revealed' : '') + '">';
      html += showAnswers ? ('x = ' + p.answer) : 'x = ___';
      html += '</div>';
      html += '</div>';
    }

    grid.innerHTML = html;
  }

  function renderAnswerKey() {
    var answerGrid = document.getElementById('answerGrid');
    var html = '';
    for (var i = 0; i < problems.length; i++) {
      html += '<div class="answer-item"><span class="q">' + (i + 1) + '.</span><span class="a">x = ' + problems[i].answer + '</span></div>';
    }
    answerGrid.innerHTML = html;
  }

  function updateAnswerVisibility() {
    var showAnswers = document.getElementById('toggleAnswers').checked;
    var answerKey = document.getElementById('answerKey');
    if (showAnswers) { answerKey.classList.remove('hidden'); } else { answerKey.classList.add('hidden'); }
    renderProblems();
  }

  document.getElementById('btnGenerate').addEventListener('click', generateProblems);
  document.getElementById('btnPrint').addEventListener('click', function() { window.print(); });
  document.getElementById('toggleAnswers').addEventListener('change', updateAnswerVisibility);
  generateProblems();
</script>
